Ahead of his medical trip to London today, President Muhammadu Buhari met with the nation's Security Chiefs at the Presidential Villa, giving them matching orders to identify bandits, kidnappers, and their sponsors and take them out.  Briefing State House correspondents after the meeting, the National Security Adviser, Major-General Babagana Monguno (retd), said the President warned that a situation where bandits and kidnappers are dictating the pace in the fight against insecurity will no longer be tolerated, mandating armed forces to be more proactive to haunt down the criminal elements.  The NSA added that President Buhari also insisted that all the decisions approved at the National Security Council meeting last month including a ban on mining activities in Zamfara as well as a no-fly zone remain enforced until further notice to curb the rising insecurity in the country. The NSA conveyed the president‘s warning and displeasure over certain elements working in cahoot with criminals in and outside the country exploiting the minefields of Zamfara state and those capitalizing on the loopholes in some security agencies.  Our Correspondent, Raliat Adenekan reports that present at the meeting includes the Chief of Defence Staff, General Lucky Irabor; Chief of Army Staff, Lieutenant-General Ibrahim Attahiru; Chief of Naval Staff; Vice Admiral Awwal Zubairu; and Chief of Air Staff, Air Marshal Isiaka Amoo. Vice-President Yemi Osinbajo; National Security Adviser to the President, Maj.-Gen Babagana Monguno (retd.); the Chief of Staff to the President, Ibrahim Gambari; Secretary to the Government of the Federation, Boss Mustapha, amongst others, were also at the meeting.